title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 10-5 police pistol with extras
postcontent:
This is a unique opportunity to own the gun, holster, and belt used by a police officer in New Jersey. This police package comes to us from an estate sale.
The revolver is a Smith & Wesson Model blued 10-5 that shows "character" and wears it with pride! This was the everyday carry weapon for this police officer until his retirement many years ago. Bore and cylinder are clean and everything feels tight. The rear sights and front ramp have white paint lightly dabbed on for the "old school" edition of fiber optic sights we have today.
The revolver has lots of holster wear and some light freckling in a few spots, but I think it is in better aesthetic condition than I would have expected from a career long everyday use and carry gun. The grips closely resemble custom-made dark walnut Bull's-eye target thumb rest grips. There is some wear in a couple of areas, primarily on the inside corners where they rubbed while in the holster.
My experience with Model 10-5 revolvers is that they are really fine shooters with nice triggers. I took this one out to the gun range tonight thinking I would shoot the handful of loose .38 caliber I had in a range bag just to make sure it fired okay. That was just a tease, as I ended up shooting that handful and a box of 50 Remington factory ammunition. It is a really good shooting gun with a nice trigger and the custom grips made for a really comfortable hold and lack of felt recoil.
The holster is a Jay-Pee Spring Lock Safety Swivel Holster that features a trigger guard click retention button to keep the pistol securely inside the holster until it can easily be removed with a push of the finger as you draw the pistol. It also has space on the belt to hold a dozen .38 Special bullets.
The belt is a Bianchi 42 with adjustable sizing and quick connection prongs.
This is a really cool police package that will easily take you back in time to when this officer carried his gun with this belt and holster.Contact me for additional pictures. 
Local face-to-face cash sale only. Buyer must be at least 21, Oklahoma resident able to legally buy a firearm in Oklahoma, and must have a current valid Oklahoma issued picture ID. No exceptions.

title: For Sale:  Russian M1895 Nagant Revolver - great condition!
postcontent: The Nagant M1895 Revolver is a seven-shot, gas-seal revolver designed and produced by Belgian industrialist Léon Nagant for the Russian Empire.The Nagant M1895 is chambered for a proprietary cartridge, 7.62×38mmR, and featured an unusual "gas-seal" system, in which the cylinder moves forward when the gun is cocked, to close the gap between the cylinder and the barrel, providing a boost to the muzzle velocity of the fired projectile and allowing the weapon to be suppressed.This particular example is in great condition, date stamp of 1944 Tula, finish in great condition with a downright beautiful bore.  I am selling along with 250 rounds of PPU new production non-corrosive factory style ammo, and the original milsurp holster and cleaning rod (plus a couple old corrosive milsurp rounds).  It's really fun to shoot and quite accurate at 25 meters although I wouldn't necessarily recommend it for personal defense.CASH ONLY - NO TRADES - Serious inquiries only - I have specifically priced this at my cost for the gun and ammo, prices have appreciated so I don't think you'll find a better deal on the internet, and that's not even counting the shipping and transfer you won't have to pay by buying locally from me.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 94 - 30 WCF
postcontent: Winchester Model 94 in 30 WCF for sale.  Manufacture date via serial number 1062*** puts this rifle as having been made between 1928-29.  What weapon like this isn't made better with a story?  This particular weapon was pulled from a fishing boat in the Republic of Panama in 1979 by a US Army intelligence officer investigating whether or not the boat owner was aiding Russia at a time when gun running / supplying to non-US interests was hot in the region.  The thought was the boat owner would ferry either Russian assets or weapons to the city of Colon (Atlantic entrance to the canal) from Russian submarines miles outside the break wall for Limon Bay.  The Panama Canal was finished and operational in 1914 - so the question remains as to how this rifle ended up there, but since Panama was a poor country back then it's likely this weapon was brought down there at some point.  Sure be interesting to figure out how it got there...The rifle was in pretty rough shape when confiscated - slime and mold on the stock was removed to reveal interesting worm burrowing patterns.  As far as I know this weapon is fully operational and the last time fired was in 1980.  It's been getting dusty ever since.  I've got plenty of pictures, can send you upon request.  Expect the sale to go through the FFL process locally.  We can work out the details.  All offers considered, trades possibly...  Thanks for looking...Update: Rifle checked by FFL / gun smith tinkerer and no pitting / rust in receiver.  Also, barrel is clean with good grooving.  FYI...

postcontent: For sale is a post-war Walther P38 in 9mm Luger. The pistol is early post-war production and is marked P38. This weapon is a former German Army (Bunduswheir) pistol built in March of 1959. Complete with Bunduswheir property marks as well as acceptance marks from the German Federal Office of Defense Technology and Procurement. The pistol functions flawlessly, and is in surplus "very good" condition. The barrel has a mirror bright bore, strong lands and grooves, and has an excellent crown. Included is two magazines; both marked Walther P38, one is dated May of 1961 and the other is dated April of 1963, and both have acceptance stamps. Also included is a leather Bunduswheir duty holster (marked June of 1963).The P38 was a benchmark in the development of automatic pistols. It features a safety/decocker and a loaded chamber indicator. It is detachable magazine fed (8+1 rounds), and is single to double action. Known for its reliability, this design replaced the Luger as the issue sidearm of the German Army in WWII, and served with the Bunduswheir until 2004.Asking $550.00, will consider trades for firearms or ammo plus cash.Must be willing to meet in the Seattle, Tacoma, Federal Way, Auburn, or Renton area.
